you hear me. I’m for putting him out of his trouble s.”

“S o’ m I ,” says Pack ard, very qui et.

“Blame it, I’d sor ter begun to think you was n ’t. Well, then, that’s all
right. Le’s go and do it.”

“Hold on a minute; I hain’t had my say y it. You listen to me.
S hoo ting ’s good, but there’s qui e ter ways if the things got to be
done. But what I say is this: it ain’t good sense to go cour t ’n’
around after a hal ter if you can git at what you’re up to in some way
that’s jist as good and at the same time don’t bring you into no re sk s.
Ain’t that so?”

“You bet it is. But how you goin’ to manage it this time?”

“Well, my idea is this: we’ll rust le around and gather up whatever
pick in ’s we’ve over looked in the statero om s, and shove for shore and
