“Why, there’s somebody com e! I wonder who ’ti s? Why, I do believe it’s
a strang er. Jim my ” ( that’s one of the childr en ), “ run and tell Li ze to
put on another plate for din ner .”

Everybody made a rush for the front door, because, of course, a
stranger don’t come every year, and so he lays over the
yaller- fever, for interest, when he does come. Tom was over the stile
and starting for the house; the wagon was spinning up the road for the
