us. My practice had ste a dily in crea sed, and as I happened to live at no
very great distance from Paddington St ation, I got a few pati ents from
among the offi ci als. One of the se, whom I had cur ed of a painful and
l ing ering disea se, was never weary of adverti sing my vir tu es and of
endeavouring to send me on every suffer er over whom he might have any
influ ence.

One morning, at a little before seven o’clock, I was awa k ened by the
maid tapping at the door to announ ce that two men had come from
Paddington and were waiting in the consul ting- room. I dressed
hurried ly, for I knew by experience that rail way cases were seldom
trivi al, and hast ened down stair s. As I descen ded, my old ally, the
gu ard, came out of the room and closed the door ti ghtly behind him.

“I’ve got him here,” he whispered, jer king his thumb over his shoulder ;
“ he’s all right.”

“What is it, then?” I asked, for his manner suggested that it was some
strange creature which he had ca ged up in my room.

“It’s a new pati ent ,” he whisper ed. “I thought I’d bring him round
myself; then he couldn’t slip away. There he is, all safe and sound. I
